{
  "texts": [
    "According to Holmqvist et al. (2011), RMS-S2S precision varies between 0.01-0.05 • for tower-mounted eye trackers and 0.03 -1.03 • for remote eye trackers.",
    "For head-mounted eye trackers, precision has been reported to be in the range 0.09 -0.35 • (Hooge, Niehorster, Hessels, Benjamins, & Nyström, 2023).",
    "High precision is required to resolve small amplitude eye movements that otherwise may be obscured by noise in the eye-tracker signal (Collewijn & Kowler, 2008; Poletti & Rucci, 2016), and reduces the need for signal processing (e.g., filtering) when classifying raw data samples into eyemovement events such as fixations and saccades (Nyström & Holmqvist, 2010).",
    "High precision may also be beneficial in human-computer interaction when gaze is used to, for instance click a button (Špakov, 2012; Feit et al., 2017).",
    "There are situations where low precision may be sufficient."
  ]
}